r to those of iron. The impact on industrial relations and on the environment of the yards was enormous. Concentrating on the yard at Chatham, the book examines how the day-to-day running of a major centre of industrial production changed during this period of transition. The Admiralty decision to build at Chatham the Achilles, the first iron ship to be constructed in a royal dockyard, placed that yard at the forefront of technological change. Had Chatham failed to complete the task satisfactorily, the future of the royal dockyards might have been very different.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aNavy-yards and naval stationsvSourcesxHistoryy19th centuryzEnglandzChatham (Kent). 0aNavy-yards and naval stationszEnglandzChatham (Kent)vSourcesxHistoryy19th century. 4aMaritime History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Naval.2bisacsh  aAdmiralty.  aChatham.  aDockyards.  aMedway.  aPax Britannica.  aPortsmouth.  aThe Victorian Navy.  aThe later Georgian Navy.  aWoolwich.1 aMacDougall, Phillip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781003122586423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781003122586/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles